main event: On October 7, 1956, a ground-radar observation was made in Odebolt, Iowa, lasting for 11 minutes, where a single object was seen moving southwest. The conclusion was that it was a balloon, but the lights of the object suggested a definite structure.
interesting points: The observation lasted for 11 minutes, providing a detailed account of the object's movements.
The lights of the object indicated a definite structure, despite the conclusion that it was a balloon.
The estimated size of the object was likely the cause of the reflection of bright lights.
The report includes information about the altitude and speed of the object at different intervals.
It was observed that the object moved swiftly to the west, disappeared, and then reappeared while heading southwest.
